      <section class="detail-block">
        <h2>Application Scenarios</h2>
        <div class="scenario-list">
          <div class="scenario-item">
            <h3>Bearing Housing and Support in Industrial Machinery</h3>
            <p>Bearing brackets support rolling element bearings that carry shaft loads in industrial drives, conveyors, and rotating equipment. The bracket's bore position accuracy, face perpendicularity, and structural stiffness determine bearing alignment, which directly affects bearing load distribution, running temperature, and service life. CNC milling ensures that bearing bracket geometry meets the design requirements without the dimensional variation of cast or welded alternatives.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="scenario-item">
            <h3>Motor and Gearbox Mounting Structures</h3>
            <p>Brackets that mount motors and gearboxes to machine frames must position the drive output shaft in precise alignment with the driven shaft. Misalignment causes coupling wear, vibration, increased bearing loads, and shaft fatigue. Precision CNC-milled bearing brackets maintain the positional relationship between mounting features to the tolerances required for correct drive alignment without iterative shimming or realignment after installation.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="scenario-item">
            <h3>Automation System Axis Support Components</h3>
            <p>Linear and rotary automation axes use bearing brackets to support guide rails, ball screws, and rotary shafts at the precision required for accurate positioning. The bracket's dimensional consistency across a batch ensures that all axis assemblies in a multi-unit machine are geometrically identical, simplifying commissioning and maintaining consistent machine performance across units.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="detail-block">
        <h2>Why CNC Milling for Bearing Brackets?</h2>
        <p>Cast or welded bearing brackets are often used for large structural applications, but they introduce dimensional variability and internal stress that can affect bearing alignment. CNC milling produces bearing brackets with the consistent geometry, bore position accuracy, and face flatness that precision bearing installations require. For applications where bearing life and alignment are critical, the investment in a CNC-milled bracket versus a cast alternative pays back in reduced maintenance and longer equipment service intervals. Contact us with your drawing or application description to discuss the right approach for your bearing bracket requirements.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="detail-block faq-block">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">What bore position tolerance can you achieve for bearing brackets?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Bearing bore position tolerance depends on the bracket size and configuration. Typical CNC milling achieves ±0.05mm positional accuracy for standard bearing bracket geometries. Tighter tolerances are available for precision axis applications — specify your requirement in the drawing and we will confirm achievability before quoting.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">What materials are suitable for precision bearing brackets?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Material selection depends on load, environment, and weight requirements. Aluminum alloy (6061, 7075) is used for weight-sensitive applications. Carbon steel provides higher strength and stiffness for heavy-load applications. Stainless steel is used for corrosive or washdown environments. Material is specified in the customer drawing.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">Can you machine multiple bearing bores in a single bracket with precise relative positioning?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Yes. Multi-bore brackets are a standard CNC milling application. All bore positions are machined in a single setup where possible to minimize positional errors from setup changes. Relative bore position tolerances are confirmed at quotation.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">Do you offer surface treatment for bearing brackets?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Yes. Available surface treatments include anodizing (aluminum), zinc plating (steel), nickel plating, and powder coating. Surface treatment is specified in the order based on corrosion protection and hardness requirements.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">Can you produce a small prototype quantity before committing to batch production?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Yes. We produce prototype quantities for dimensional verification and assembly fit checks before batch production. This is the standard process for new drawing-based orders with tight tolerance requirements.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">What inspection documentation do you provide?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Dimensional inspection reports are available on request, covering critical dimensions specified in the drawing. For applications requiring full traceability, material certificates and inspection records can be provided. Specify your documentation requirements at the order stage.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

